    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-01-31T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-01-31T18:00:00-05:00" n="179"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d179">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 U.S.S.R./167b: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WJC1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wiley</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-01-31T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 31, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>24. <persName corresp="#p_TAA1">Troyanovsky</persName> this afternoon rejected my
                    proposal of last September for settlement of the question of debts, claims and
                    credits and made no new proposal. I am issuing a statement for publication 9
                    P.M. this evening which is being cabled to you.</p>
                <p>It is anticipated that the Export-Import Bank will be abolished immediately, that
                    the Naval and Air Attachés will be withdrawn, the Consulate General abolished,
                    and the personnel of the Embassy reduced. Instructions will be cabled covering
                    these matters.</p>
                <p>In discussing these actions with members of the Soviet Government and others in
                    Moscow you should endeavor to convey clearly the fact that the Government of the
                    United States has desired and does desire the most friendly cooperation with the
                    Soviet Union but that <persName corresp="#p_LMM1">Litvinov</persName> has shown
                    so little disposition to permit the development of friendly relations with the
                    United States that the Government of the United States is convinced that no real
                    friendship can be developed so long as he adheres to his present attitude.</p>
                <p>Ambassador thinks it desirable that both <persName corresp="#p_NDR1"
                        >Nimmer</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_WTD1">White</persName> in their
                    farewell conversations with <persName corresp="#p_VKE1">Voroshilov</persName>
                    should refer to the numerous unnecessary obstacles to the development of
                    Soviet-American friendship which have been created by <persName
                        corresp="#p_LMM1">Litvinov</persName>.</p>
                <p>The Ambassador will return to Moscow as soon as he has recovered from his present
                    illness, which is not a diplomatic invention but a streptococcus infection.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
